### Legal and Educational Perspectives

- **Legal Framework:**  
  The Supreme Court case *Board of Education v. Pico* (1982) established that removing books from school libraries based solely on disagreement with their content violates the First Amendment. However, schools retain some discretion in selecting age-appropriate materials ([National Coalition Against Censorship, 2021](https://ncac.org/resource/book-challenge-resource-center)).

- **Educational Selection vs. Censorship:**  
  Professional educators and librarians emphasize the importance of distinguishing between censorship (removal based on personal/political beliefs) and selection (choosing materials for educational merit). Selection should be guided by objective criteria and involve trained professionals ([Miner, 2021](https://rethinkingschools.org/articles/reading-writing-and-censorship)).

- **Parental Involvement:**  
  Policies often allow parents to opt their children out of certain readings, balancing parental rights and student access. Blanket bans affecting all students raise constitutional and ethical concerns ([National Coalition Against Censorship, 2021](https://ncac.org/resource/book-challenge-resource-center)).

